The dragon, symbolizing rain-bringing deities or messengers of the gods, is often featured in taikodai decoration. The fabric straps used to secure the "futon" (mattress-like tiers) atop the float are embroidered with golden dragons, and tassels on the straps symbolize rain. Thus, in regions like {{ill|Kagawa Prefecture|ja|香川県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kagawa Prefecture|qq=}} and eastern {{ill|Ehime Prefecture|ja|愛媛県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ehime Prefecture|qq=}}, taikodai have historically been associated more with rainmaking rituals than with mikoshi.
While taikodai do not carry divine spirits like mikoshi, some regions consider the futon or roof portions as sacred vessels where spirits may reside. For this reason, women were traditionally prohibited from touching taikodai in certain areas. Boys who play the drums inside may dress elaborately and avoid touching the ground, much like traditional {{ill|Chigo|ja|稚児|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chigo|qq=}}.
Taikodai are distinct from hikiyama floats in that they are carried rather than pulled. This makes them easier to maneuver in mountainous areas or over uneven terrain. They are often raised high overhead in displays known as "sashiage" (差し上げ) and may also be shaken, rotated, or competed in lifting contests.
== Structure == [[File:Nadanokenkamatsuri-yatai42.jpg|thumb|150px|Interior drum of a taikodai at the {{ill|Nada Fighting Festival|ja|灘のけんか祭り|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nada Fighting Festival|qq=}}]] [[File:大阪 堺 西湊 ふとん太鼓.jpg|thumb|200px|Futon Taiko from {{ill|Sakai|ja|堺市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakai|qq=}}, Osaka Prefecture]]
- The base, called the "taiwa" (台輪), supports the drum, carrying poles, railings, and vertical pillars, with a roof of futon or heavy tiers. - The futon (重) tiers vary from 2 to 8 in number, depending on regional tradition. - Ornamental features such as tassels, decorative straps, and embroidered dragons are common. - Modern taikodai may use lightweight materials for ease of transport.
For further details on specific styles, see: - {{ill|Futon Taiko|ja|ふとん太鼓|1=Futon Daiko|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Futon Taiko|13=User:Immanuelle/Futon Daiko|qq=}} - {{ill|Taikodai|lt=Taikodai|lt=Chōsa|ja|頂載|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chōsa|qq=}}
